1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,803
It is a weekend. You are not at school. You are on your
own phone, and you post something — angry, crude, the

2
00:00:09,803 --> 00:00:18,328
kind of thing teenagers post when they are upset . Can
your school punish you for that? In 2021, a

3
00:00:18,328 --> 00:00:24,722
fourteen-year-old's disappearing Snapchat reached the
Supreme Court of the United States, and the answer it

4
00:00:24,722 --> 00:00:32,820
gave shapes the rights of every student — and every
parent — in the age of the phone .

5
00:00:33,278 --> 00:00:41,555
Students do have free speech. A famous 1969 case said
so: young people do not "shed their constitutional

6
00:00:41,555 --> 00:00:49,833
rights at the schoolhouse gate" . But schools can still
limit speech that seriously disrupts the school. For

7
00:00:49,833 --> 00:00:58,110
decades, that line was easy to draw, because school
speech happened at school. Then everyone got a phone,

8
00:00:58,110 --> 00:01:08,226
and the gate disappeared. Now a student's words can be
posted from a bedroom at midnight and be in front of the

9
00:01:08,226 --> 00:01:16,963
whole school by morning. Over the next twelve minutes:
the post, the punishment, and the moment the Court had

10
00:01:16,963 --> 00:01:22,022
to decide where a school's power over your voice
actually ends.

11
00:01:22,480 --> 00:01:30,653
Her name is Brandi Levy. In 2017 she is fourteen, a
student at Mahanoy Area High School in Pennsylvania, and

12
00:01:30,653 --> 00:01:34,332
a cheerleader — on the junior varsity squad .

13
00:01:34,790 --> 00:01:44,117
She wants to be on varsity. She does not make it. She is
told to stay on JV, while a younger student moves up. To

14
00:01:44,117 --> 00:01:48,221
a fourteen-year-old, this is not a small thing; it
stings .

15
00:01:48,679 --> 00:01:58,067
So, on a Saturday, off school grounds, at a local
convenience store, she does what a lot of frustrated

16
00:01:58,067 --> 00:02:06,961
teenagers do. She opens Snapchat, takes a photo of
herself and a friend with their middle fingers raised,

17
00:02:06,961 --> 00:02:16,349
and adds a caption — short, blunt, and full of
profanity, aimed at school, at softball, at cheer, at

18
00:02:16,349 --> 00:02:26,231
everything . We are not going to repeat it, but you can
imagine the energy of it: pure, unfiltered teenage

19
00:02:26,231 --> 00:02:26,725
anger.

20
00:02:27,183 --> 00:02:36,075
Here is the thing about Snapchat. The post is supposed
to vanish. It goes out to her friends — about two

21
00:02:36,075 --> 00:02:45,391
hundred and fifty of them — and then it is gone . But
"gone" is a myth. Someone takes a screenshot. The

22
00:02:45,391 --> 00:02:53,013
screenshot travels. And it lands exactly where she least
wants it: in front of the cheerleading coaches .

23
00:02:53,471 --> 00:03:03,959
And it is worth sitting with how ordinary this was. No
threat. No named target. No plan. Just a teenager, off

24
00:03:03,959 --> 00:03:13,948
the clock, cursing her own disappointment into a phone —
the most forgettable kind of speech there is, until a

25
00:03:13,948 --> 00:03:16,445
screenshot made it permanent .

26
00:03:16,903 --> 00:03:26,339
The school's response is firm. For that post — made on a
weekend, off campus, on her own phone — Brandi is

27
00:03:26,339 --> 00:03:31,915
suspended from the junior varsity cheerleading team for
the entire upcoming year .

28
00:03:32,373 --> 00:03:40,673
To the school, this is simple discipline: a cheerleader
publicly trashing the program she is part of. To Brandi

29
00:03:40,673 --> 00:03:48,973
and her parents, it is something else: a public school
reaching off campus, into a weekend, to punish a

30
00:03:48,973 --> 00:03:57,272
teenager for words it did not like. They sue,
represented by the ACLU, and the question rides all the

31
00:03:57,272 --> 00:04:00,330
way up to the Supreme Court .

32
00:04:00,788 --> 00:04:09,754
To understand the stakes, you have to go back to that
1969 case, Tinker v. Des Moines. Students had worn black

33
00:04:09,754 --> 00:04:18,293
armbands to school to protest a war, the school punished
them, and the Supreme Court sided with the students .

34
00:04:18,751 --> 00:04:27,567
Tinker set the rule that still governs student speech.
Yes, students have First Amendment rights. But a school

35
00:04:27,567 --> 00:04:35,404
can discipline speech that would "substantially disrupt"
the school — that genuinely interferes with running it.

36
00:04:35,404 --> 00:04:43,730
Armbands worn silently did not cross that line. A
protest that shut the school down might .

37
00:04:44,188 --> 00:04:53,166
Those students had worn the armbands in 1965 to mourn
the dead of the Vietnam War, after the school banned

38
00:04:53,166 --> 00:05:00,348
that specific protest in advance. The Court's answer was
blunt: neither students nor teachers shed their

39
00:05:00,348 --> 00:05:07,980
constitutional rights at the schoolhouse gate — but a
school may still act when speech would substantially

40
00:05:07,980 --> 00:05:09,775
disrupt its work .

41
00:05:10,233 --> 00:05:18,669
For fifty years, that test worked, because it had a
place. School speech meant speech at school — in the

42
00:05:18,669 --> 00:05:24,151
hallway, the classroom, the assembly. A school's
authority had edges you could see.

43
00:05:24,610 --> 00:05:33,419
The phone erased those edges. When a student can
broadcast to the entire school from her own bedroom, at

44
00:05:33,419 --> 00:05:43,155
any hour, on any day, what counts as "school speech"? If
a school can punish a disruptive post made off campus,

45
00:05:43,155 --> 00:05:51,037
then in principle it can reach a student's words
twenty-four hours a day, anywhere — because almost

46
00:05:51,037 --> 00:05:57,065
anything a student says online could, in theory, ripple
back to school .

47
00:05:57,523 --> 00:06:06,437
And that is the quiet danger the case exposed. Not that
schools would punish one rude Snapchat, but that the

48
00:06:06,437 --> 00:06:14,905
logic for punishing it had no natural stopping point.
Follow it far enough, and a student never really leaves

49
00:06:14,905 --> 00:06:24,265
school at all. The gate that Tinker assumed — the line
between the school's world and the rest of a young

50
00:06:24,265 --> 00:06:26,939
person's life — had simply dissolved.

51
00:06:27,397 --> 00:06:35,828
In 2021, the Supreme Court ruled for Brandi Levy. By a
vote of eight to one, it held that the school had

52
00:06:35,828 --> 00:06:41,193
violated her First Amendment rights when it punished her
for that off-campus post .

53
00:06:41,652 --> 00:06:49,195
Justice Stephen Breyer wrote the opinion, and his
reasoning was careful. A school's special authority over

54
00:06:49,195 --> 00:06:58,624
what students say, he explained, is weaker off campus
than on. Off campus, a student is normally in the care

55
00:06:58,624 --> 00:07:07,582
of her parents, not the school. And if schools could
police student speech around the clock, that power would

56
00:07:07,582 --> 00:07:14,654
reach so far into private life that it could swallow
students' free speech entirely .

57
00:07:15,112 --> 00:07:23,230
Breyer added a thought that explains why the Court bent
toward the student. America's public schools, he wrote,

58
00:07:23,230 --> 00:07:31,349
are the "nurseries of democracy" — the place a free
society teaches the next generation to tolerate the

59
00:07:31,349 --> 00:07:39,016
speech it dislikes. A school that punishes every
unpopular off-campus word does not model that lesson; it

60
00:07:39,016 --> 00:07:40,820
teaches the opposite .

61
00:07:41,278 --> 00:07:50,731
The Court also looked at what had actually happened, and
found almost nothing. Brandi's post had caused, at most,

62
00:07:50,731 --> 00:07:59,687
a few minutes of discussion in one class. That is not
the "substantial disruption" Tinker requires. The school

63
00:07:59,687 --> 00:08:02,672
had punished frustration, not chaos .

64
00:08:03,130 --> 00:08:13,274
But — and this is the part people miss — the Court
refused to give students a blank check. It pointedly did

65
00:08:13,274 --> 00:08:22,496
not say that schools can never reach off-campus speech.
It listed the kinds of things that might still justify a

66
00:08:22,496 --> 00:08:29,873
school stepping in, even off campus: serious bullying or
harassment aimed at other students, threats, cheating,

67
00:08:29,873 --> 00:08:37,712
breaking real rules. It declined to draw one bright
line, leaving the hard cases for later .

68
00:08:38,170 --> 00:08:44,942
One justice would have gone the other way. Justice
Clarence Thomas dissented, arguing that historically

69
00:08:44,942 --> 00:08:52,618
schools had broad authority over students that did
extend beyond the campus, and that the majority was

70
00:08:52,618 --> 00:09:01,196
discarding that tradition . His was the lone vote. But
it points at the real difficulty: nobody, including the

71
00:09:01,196 --> 00:09:09,774
Court, drew a clean line — because in the age of the
phone, a clean line may not exist.

72
00:09:10,232 --> 00:09:19,493
So where does this leave you, or your kid? With a
protection that is real but deliberately fuzzy. After

73
00:09:19,493 --> 00:09:28,267
Mahanoy, a public school cannot punish a student simply
for an ordinary, off-campus, online vent that does not

74
00:09:28,267 --> 00:09:34,603
disrupt the school . Frustration on a weekend is not the
school's business.

75
00:09:35,061 --> 00:09:44,472
But it is not a wall. The same ruling keeps the door
open for the serious cases — the threat, the targeted

76
00:09:44,472 --> 00:09:53,454
harassment, the cheating ring run over a group chat .
The result is a gray zone that every student and parent

77
00:09:53,454 --> 00:09:57,731
now lives in, decided post by post, case by case.

78
00:09:58,189 --> 00:10:05,845
And notice what the Court actually protected. Not a
noble political statement, but a crude, throwaway

79
00:10:05,845 --> 00:10:14,937
Snapchat that vanished in seconds. That was on purpose.
The Court understood that free speech is tested not by

80
00:10:14,937 --> 00:10:25,463
the speech we admire, but by the speech we find petty,
or rude, or pointless — because that is the speech the

81
00:10:25,463 --> 00:10:28,334
powerful are most tempted to punish.

82
00:10:28,792 --> 00:10:35,822
A fourteen-year-old's bad weekend, captured in a
disappearing post, ended up drawing one of the most

83
00:10:35,822 --> 00:10:44,171
important lines of the smartphone era: the line between
the school's authority and the rest of a young person's

84
00:10:44,171 --> 00:10:49,883
life . The school could reach a lot. It could not reach
everything.

85
00:10:50,341 --> 00:10:59,546
We have now watched the state try to search you, track
you, and take your property — and try to police what you

86
00:10:59,546 --> 00:11:07,951
say. In every one of those fights, the pattern is the
same: a power that made sense in a smaller world,

87
00:11:07,951 --> 00:11:16,357
stretched by technology until a court has to find its
edge again. And every time, that edge looks less like a

88
00:11:16,357 --> 00:11:23,161
fence than a line drawn in pencil — ready to be moved by
whatever device comes next.

89
00:11:23,619 --> 00:11:33,047
But not every right is taken from you by a school or a
police officer. Some you hand over yourself — willingly,

90
00:11:33,047 --> 00:11:41,617
in seconds, without reading a word. The next case is
about the most common contract in modern life, the one

91
00:11:41,617 --> 00:11:48,902
you agree to constantly, that quietly signs away your
right to ever take a company to court.

92
00:11:49,360 --> 00:11:51,001
That is next time.
